          "title": "The high priest's death: the chapter's most theologically charged provision",
          "body": "Verse 6 contains the institution's most striking and least-explained provision: the manslayer is released upon the death of the reigning high priest. No explanation is given in the text for why this is the releasing event. The rabbis offered various proposals — that the high priest's intercessory failure to prevent the accidental death warranted a communal consequence, or that his death atoned vicariously for the manslayer's act. What the text establishes is the pattern without the explanation. The death of the highest priestly figure in Israel effects the release of those confined under the law's jurisdiction. The typological weight of this provision is enormous, and the New Testament author of Hebrews (6:18) explicitly invokes the cities of refuge as a type of the hope set before those who have fled for refuge to Christ. The death of a greater High Priest releases permanently those who have fled to Him — not from a city's walls but from condemnation itself."
